WEBVTT

00:08.693 --> 00:11.028
Give me your tired,

00:11.030 --> 00:13.830
your poor, your huddled...

00:13.832 --> 00:15.666
Masses. Huddled masses.

00:15.668 --> 00:18.068
Yearning to breathe free.
Come on.

00:18.070 --> 00:20.304
Your huddled masses,
yearning to breathe free.

00:20.306 --> 00:21.672
Exactly.

00:21.674 --> 00:23.140
The wretched...

00:23.142 --> 00:25.008
The wretched...

00:25.010 --> 00:26.777
The wretched refuse
of your teeming shores.

00:26.779 --> 00:29.246
Jack, you're supposed
to know this by now.

00:29.248 --> 00:30.781
It's too hard.

00:30.783 --> 00:32.149
Why do I have to
learn some stupid poem

00:32.151 --> 00:33.950
on a stupid statue anyway?

00:33.952 --> 00:35.252
Watch your language!

00:35.254 --> 00:36.753
You should get a time out.

00:36.755 --> 00:38.055
Sean.
Sorry.

00:38.057 --> 00:39.256
What's the point?

00:39.258 --> 00:41.158
I'll never need to
know this in real life.

00:41.160 --> 00:43.327
Yes, you will.
How?

00:43.329 --> 00:45.162
Say I want to be a doctor.
You really think

00:45.164 --> 00:46.930
knowing this poem's gonna
help me save someone's life?

00:46.932 --> 00:48.565
In a matter

00:48.567 --> 00:49.866
of speaking, yes.

00:49.868 --> 00:51.234
Right?

00:51.236 --> 00:53.470
Right. I was just excited

00:53.472 --> 00:55.238
to hear him say
he wanted to be a doctor.

00:55.240 --> 00:56.773
Danny.

00:58.209 --> 01:01.411
<i>Let me delay her</i>
<i>for ten minutes.</i>

01:01.413 --> 01:03.380
She can sit outside
and cool her heels.

01:03.382 --> 01:04.715
Why?

01:04.717 --> 01:05.816
Message sent.

01:05.818 --> 01:07.184
You run the NYPD.

01:07.186 --> 01:09.419
You don't have a lot of time
for this nannying nonsense.

01:09.421 --> 01:11.388
She's gonna be smarter
than that, Garrett.

01:11.390 --> 01:13.523
Then, let me at least
bring the chiefs up.

01:13.525 --> 01:15.092
She can face down
a full house.

01:15.094 --> 01:17.427
She is the duly-appointed
inspector general, Garrett.

01:17.429 --> 01:19.596
Not some accomplice
we're trying to flip.

01:19.598 --> 01:21.932
All right, how do you
want this to go down?

01:25.002 --> 01:27.504
How do I want it to go?

01:28.639 --> 01:29.806
Seriously?

01:29.808 --> 01:31.675
Okay, okay.

01:31.677 --> 01:32.876
Some activist judge rules

01:32.878 --> 01:36.146
that highly-effective
NYPD policy is infringing

01:36.148 --> 01:39.116
on the citizens' civil rights,
so then,

01:39.118 --> 01:42.219
he goes to his buddies
at Dewey, Cheatem and Howe,

01:42.221 --> 01:44.654
and says, "How would you like
to bill the city

01:44.656 --> 01:46.289
"for a couple million a year

01:46.291 --> 01:47.858
"by appointing one
of your attorneys

01:47.860 --> 01:50.727
to be inspector general
to fix what isn't broke."

01:50.729 --> 01:53.463
It didn't exactly
go down like that.

01:53.465 --> 01:54.931
That's exactly how it went down!

01:54.933 --> 01:57.868
And nowhere in that process
did anybody ever say to me,

01:57.870 --> 02:00.437
"Hey, Frank,
how'd you like it to go?"

02:00.439 --> 02:01.671
Okay.
So, it's a little late

02:01.673 --> 02:04.541
to be asking me now!

02:06.077 --> 02:07.644
Show her in!

02:12.351 --> 02:13.884
Miss Peterson.

02:15.153 --> 02:18.455
Commissioner Reagan, Inspector
General Kelly Peterson.

02:19.590 --> 02:21.658
Kelly, please.

02:21.660 --> 02:24.961
Frank. Welcome
to One Police Plaza.

02:24.963 --> 02:27.130
Thank you for
seeing me.

02:29.333 --> 02:31.301
Excuse me.

02:33.838 --> 02:36.673
So, congratulations.

02:36.675 --> 02:39.276
Look, I won't insult you
by saying

02:39.278 --> 02:41.278
I know what you probably
think of me.

02:41.280 --> 02:42.979
I think you just did.

02:42.981 --> 02:44.848
No. No, no.

02:44.850 --> 02:46.483
That was an olive branch.

02:46.485 --> 02:49.820
Well, I've never met you,
so I have no opinion of you.

02:49.822 --> 02:51.922
Oh, but you do of my position.

02:51.924 --> 02:53.957
You've been broadcasting
your feelings about it

02:53.959 --> 02:56.092
ever since the judge ruled.
Yes,

02:56.094 --> 02:58.295
but that was before
I met the actual person

02:58.297 --> 03:00.197
behind the title.

03:01.833 --> 03:04.901
Miss Peterson...

03:04.903 --> 03:07.671
we're not going
to be colleagues or teammates

03:07.673 --> 03:11.641
or whatever hope they dangled
to get you to take the job.

03:11.643 --> 03:13.410
Before I joined the firm,

03:13.412 --> 03:15.946
I was the Essex County
prosecutor.

03:15.948 --> 03:17.247
I know that.

03:17.249 --> 03:18.448
Which should
tell you

03:18.450 --> 03:22.118
that I have enormous respect
for law enforcement.

03:22.120 --> 03:23.854
Just not the NYPD.

03:23.856 --> 03:26.790
Especially the NYPD.

03:26.792 --> 03:28.892
Then why did you take this job?

03:28.894 --> 03:31.061
Because I'd heard
their commissioner was a fair

03:31.063 --> 03:33.129
and honest man
who wanted the best

03:33.131 --> 03:34.564
for his department.

03:34.566 --> 03:36.466
You heard right.

03:36.468 --> 03:39.402
But you're going about it
the wrong way.

03:40.706 --> 03:43.073
I'm not good at small talk,
either.

03:43.075 --> 03:44.608
I just thought
we should meet

03:44.610 --> 03:45.942
face-to-face.

03:45.944 --> 03:48.044
And so we have.

03:48.046 --> 03:49.746
Of course, if we
were face-to-face,

03:49.748 --> 03:51.581
I'd have to climb
up on that desk.

03:51.583 --> 03:53.650
But this will do.

03:53.652 --> 03:55.886
Thank you for coming.

03:57.221 --> 03:59.122
You have a good day.

03:59.124 --> 04:02.993
I'll see myself out.

